{
  "text": "The key idea of WASA is that for an arbitrary signal to be analyzed in the frequency domain, it's possible to choose a number of phasors, according to a certain criterion, and then weight these phasors with adaptable weights that might be adapted by iterating the well-known LMS adaptation role. Upon choosing a suitable value for the adaptation rate, these weighted phasors are equal to the DFT coefficients of the signal under consideration. Fig. 1 shows the complete schematic diagram of the WASA model. Fig. 1 . Adaptive LMS spectrum Analyzer as proposed by [CITATION_1] The signal d j is the input sampled version of the signal to be Fourier analyzed which is sampled at each time index j. The sampling time is T sec and the corresponding sampling The rest of the other phasors are the power of equation (2).",
